  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 못된 짓[作俑] : '
    value: 용(俑)은 허수아비를 말한 것인데, 장사할 때 상여 앞에 세우고 가는 것임. 《맹자》 양혜왕편(梁惠王篇)에, “중니(仲尼)는 말하기를, ‘맨 처음에 용(俑)을 만들어낸 자는 아마도 후사(後嗣)가 없을 것이다’ 하셨고, 그 주석에 ‘중니는 인류(人類)를 소중히 여기므로 처음 이것을 만들어낸 자를 미워하여 이 자는 후사가 없을 것이다’ 한 것임.”이라 하였음. 악례(惡例)를 처음으로 만들어 낸 자를 작용(作俑)이라 씀.
english:
  title: Five Teachings for My Son
  author: Kang Hee-meng
  language: eng
  text: |-
    # Teaching on Instructing My Son

    This teaching, which I call "Instruction for a Son," was written by me, a man without ambition, for my son Gui-sun as he turned from official life toward scholarship. Why do I instruct him? Because I wish to guide him where he has yet to arrive. Why do I dare offer these words when I have not first examined myself? Because though my language is plain, my intent echoes the wisdom left by the sages of old. Why do I not speak directly but hint at meaning instead? Because between father and son, words must be gentle.

    When my son resigned from office to pursue learning, some said, "One must not refuse rank and salary," while others said, "One must seize learning while young." With such conflicting counsel, how could he not waver in his choice? So I appealed to him through greater principles, urging him to commit to his studies. Yet fearing something might be overlooked, I set down these words in writing and urged him: "Contemplate these daily. Penetrate their meaning deeply, and the path forward will become clear, the way to virtue will grow familiar, and these words will not lack for value."

    I have read how the great Master Zhu wrote to his eldest son: "The two characters for diligence and carefulness are the foundation. Build upon them and infinite good things await. Though I dare not promise this, I wish it for you. Reverse them and infinite troubles multiply. Though I wish not to speak it, I cannot help but worry. If you truly love learning, even at home you may read, write, and penetrate principle—you need not leave your parents' side. Yet since you cannot manage this, I send you away lest worldly concerns distract you from your purpose. If you go forth with courage and determination, if you reform your old habits and commit yourself wholly to diligence and care, then I hold hope. Otherwise, returning home unchanged, you will be the same person as before. What face will you show to your parents, relatives, neighbors, and old friends? The honor of your ancestors rests upon this one journey."

    Ah, how the concern and affection of the ancient wise when teaching their sons shine through! A father's teaching of his son is like a farmer's cultivation of grain. If the grain fails to grow, famine comes. If the son is not well taught, calamity follows. How could I ever slack in the methods of fertilizing and weeding, or in the ways of instruction and encouragement? And now, in my twilight years, I have suffered the loss of so many children, leaving but two. Summer days and winter nights bring unceasing sorrow. In crowds of people, tears fall unbidden. I have become something strange and pitiable. What depth of hope do I place upon you!

    This is why I write. Let fathers, hearing my heart, teach their sons well. Let sons, moved by my sorrow, honor their parents. Then perhaps these words will not be mere wind.

    # The Tale of the Thief's Son

    There was a man who made theft his trade. He taught his son all his arts. The son was gifted and believed himself far superior to his father. When they stole together, the son would always go in first and come out last, leaving light things but taking the heavy, his ears sharp to hear distant sounds, his eyes keen in darkness. The band of thieves praised him, and he boasted to his father: "I miss nothing of your technique, and my strength exceeds yours. With this, what cannot I accomplish?"

    The father replied: "You are not yet ready. Wisdom gained through learning has limits; what springs from your own heart knows no bounds. You are still far from mastery."

    The son said: "But in thieving, gathering wealth is the measure of skill. I already exceed you in results. My years are few—when I reach your age, I will have still greater skills."

    The father answered: "Not yet. My methods can breach walls and uncover secret treasures. But one misstep brings ruin close behind. To leave no trace, to respond to circumstance without rigidity—this only those who have truly discovered something within themselves can do. You have not yet reached this."

    The son paid no heed. One night, the father took his son to a wealthy house and sent him into the treasury. Absorbed in gathering valuables, the son did not notice his father lock the door from outside and make noise to alert the household. The owner came running out, and seeing the lock still secure, returned inside. The son, trapped in the vault, heard the commotion. In desperation, he scratched at the walls, making sounds like rats gnawing. The owner heard and thought: "Rats are damaging our stores. We must look."

    When the owner brought a lamp and unlocked the door, the son fled. The household pursued him. The son, desperate, fled around a pond and threw stones into the water. His pursuers cried out: "The thief jumped in!" While they searched the banks, the son escaped and returned, angry at his father: "Even beasts protect their young. What wrong have I done that you treat me this way?"

    The father smiled: "Now you are ready to walk alone under heaven. Listen well: the skills people learn from others have defined limits. What arises from your own mind finds infinite application. How much more so when hardship forges courage and danger teaches wisdom! When I put you in danger, I was protecting you. When I seemed to trap you, I was saving you. Without the terror of the vault and pursuit, would you have discovered the wisdom of sounding like rats and throwing stones? Through difficulty you found your own cleverness. Facing crisis, you invented what was needed. Once your mind opens this way, it cannot be confused again. Now you walk alone under heaven."

    And indeed, the son became a thief without equal in all the land.

    Theft is the basest of arts, yet even it requires self-discovery to be invincible. How much more so when a gentleman pursues virtue and fame! Those born to office and privilege, inheriting status, often know nothing of goodness or learning. Proud in their position, they surpass their ancestors in nothing. This is like the thief's son boasting to his father. But if one can cast aside rank, live humbly, abandon excess, pursue learning with quiet dedication, study principle deeply, resist being swept away by fashion—then one may equal others and win true recognition. To act or refrain from acting, to advance or withdraw—all becomes fitting. This resembles the thief's son, who through hardship discovered his own wisdom and walked alone under heaven. You too are close to this. Do not fear the vault and pursuit. Seek to discover something true within your own heart.

    # The Tale of the Snake-Eater

    In the land of Mingzhou, precious medicinal herbs grew in abundance. The medicine bureau sent a doctor who would travel there every other year to gather them. One doctor became responsible for this task and journeyed to Mingzhou repeatedly.

    On his first visit, the herb-gatherers pointed out one or two of their number and said: "Those are snake-eaters." Everyone shuddered, refusing to share their meal or sit near them, treating them as less than human.

    Two years later, the doctor returned. The scorn had diminished. Those once called "snake-eaters" had become familiar companions, with no shame attached.

    Two years further, he saw no one called a "snake-eater" and heard no mockery spoken.

    Observing closely, he saw people carrying wooden bows and small bent sticks with cord. They would venture into the deep forests and, when meeting a snake—large or small—they would press it down with the bow. As the snake reared and opened its mouth, they would use the curved stick to break its teeth. They would skin it, pack the hide, and later salt and roast it. People ate greedily, leaving nothing. Over time, many died from the poison.

    Ah, snakes crawl and writhe, covered in scales, dwelling on earth. Even a fool knows to despise them and flee. If forced near, who does not feel revulsion and trembling? This is human nature. The people of Mingzhou at first rejected the practice, many keeping their natural revulsion. Later, rejection waned and practice spread, though some maintained their nature unstained by fashion. Finally, across the entire region, none questioned it. Mockery ceased. All grew comfortable with what was once foul. Human nature was thoroughly veiled, and none could judge right from wrong.

    Could all the people of one province have lost their heavenly nature and remained ignorant? No. Someone must have begun this perversion. How did they do it? They said: "The snake is merely a creature, like fish or insects. It is plump and fragrant, easy to catch near people. Is it so different from the black carp? Let us try it."

    When no harm came from tasting, the hesitation faded. Through months and years, a habit formed. Before long, shame vanished entirely. At that point, who knew snake-eating was shameful or poison was fearful? Those who had once denounced it now joined in: "This person also partakes! Why should taste be my alone? Perhaps there is a subtle flavor others have discovered. Was my former rejection mistaken? Who can say what he perceives?"

    Thus, through mutual influence, none saw the wrong. How sad! Gentlemen succumb the same way to wealth, status, and sensuality. Everyone knows gluttony and debauchery bring shame, that such stains bring ruin. Yet when they sample these in their hearts, shame fades. Have you heard scorn and mockery? You must discern the beginning. Do not be careless.

    # The Tale of Climbing the Mountain

    A man of Lu had three sons: A was steady but lame, B loved adventure and was whole, C was light-minded but swift and powerful beyond others. In daily labor, C excelled, B came second, and A, though working diligently, barely completed his tasks. One day, B and C agreed to race up Mount Tai to see the sunrise from Riyuan Peak, and A also prepared to go.

    B and C smiled at each other and said: "Mount Tai's peak rises above the clouds, overlooking all under heaven. Only the sure-footed can climb it. What use for a cripple to even think of it?"

    A smiled back: "I will merely follow behind you. It would be miraculous fortune to reach the end."

    At Mount Tai's base, B and C warned A: "We will leap across chasms without a blink. You go ahead."

    A accepted this. C fell behind at the mountain's foot while B reached the midway point as darkness fell. A walked on without pause, reaching the summit by nightfall and sleeping at a lodge. At dawn, he watched the sun rise from the sea.

    Back home, their father asked each what they saw.

    C said: "At the mountain's base, the day was still young. Relying on my agility, I wandered every path, gathering rare flowers and strange plants. But darkness fell suddenly while I rambled. I slept in a cave. Cold wind cut my ears, the stream roared loud, foxes and jackals circled crying. My spirit grew heavy. I wanted to display my strength and run, but fear of tigers and leopards stopped me."

    B said: "I saw countless peaks like spiraling shells, blue cliffs like sharpened iron. I climbed and descended without missing a path. But each peak was higher, each slope steeper. My legs grew weary. I barely reached the midpoint when the sun set. I rested at the rocks, surrounded by cloud and mist so thick I could not see three feet ahead. My clothes and shoes grew cold and damp. The peak above still seemed distant, the base below even farther. I simply remained there, unable to proceed."

    A said: "I thought of my twisted feet and uncertain steps. I chose one path and never stopped, even fearing time would not suffice. How could I wander about with idle eyes? Giving all my strength, climbing foot by foot, I reached what the servants called the ultimate height. Looking up, I could almost touch heaven's carriage. Looking down, the layered forests stretched endlessly. The mountains stood like sealed walls, the valleys like wrinkles on skin. As the sun sank into the sea below, all turned dark. Looking sideways, stars shone together bright enough to read by my palm. Truly wondrous.

    "Sleep had barely come when a cock crowed. The east grew bright. Crimson light spread across the sea, golden waves reached toward heaven. Red phoenix and golden serpent stirred within the light. Then slowly, slowly, the red wheel rose and fell, and before my eyes opened fully, great brightness filled the vast sky. Truly extraordinary!"

    The father said: "It is as your stories tell. Zilu had courage, Ranyou had skill, yet neither reached the Master's wall. It was Zeng Zi who reached it through the stubbornness of Lu. Remember this, my sons.

    "Ah, the order of advancing in virtue and the path to achievement—all who climb from low to high, from small to great, follow this way. Do not limit yourself through pride in strength. Do not abandon yourself through laziness. Then even the lame may exert themselves. Do not be careless."

    # The Tale of Three Pheasants

    Pheasants by nature are lustful and love to fight. One male leads many females to feed and drink in the mountain valleys. When spring and summer come, with dense growth all around, the females sing out. As soon as a male hears the sound, he spreads his wings and comes, caring nothing that men are near—for he rages that another male keeps these females.

    The hunter knows this. He makes a blind of leaves, captures a male pheasant as bait, enters the forest with a pipe made from a hollow reed. He blows the pipe to imitate a female's call and moves the captured bird to act as if courting. The wild male arrives in fury. The hunter throws his net and catches dozens daily.

    I asked the hunter: "Do all pheasants desire the same? Are there no differences?"

    He said: "Though types vary greatly, there are roughly three kinds. In the sparse hills where thousands of pheasants live, I catch daily. Some approach once and are caught on the first throw. Some approach twice before the second throw catches them. Some approach once, escape my throw, and never return—ever. Why?"

    "One kind," he explained, "when I stand at my blind with my pipe and bait, hears and watches, glides down lightly, comes like thrown stone, lands like stuck arrow. The pheasant draws near without blinking. One throw—caught. This pheasant is most entranced, having forgotten all danger. This is the kind most easily taken.

    "Another kind: at first call and movement, pretends not to hear. At second call, hesitates slightly. It flies and circles, hovering a man's height above ground. It approaches as if fearful, lands as if thinking. Yet desire overwhelms its caution and it nears me. I throw once and would catch it, but it had anticipated and flees. Angered, I return the next day when it relaxes. I improve my blind, approach carefully, call again—now more convincingly. I barely manage to catch it. This pheasant is somewhat wary, knowing danger exists.

    "A third kind: at the mere sound of footsteps, it bursts up crying out, soars toward clouds, darts into forest—never looking back. These are hardest to catch. I swear inwardly, 'If I cannot catch this one, I should abandon my art.' I go daily to the hills, watching from every angle. Its suspicion remains constant. So I hide my form, still my breath, stand like dead wood. Only when I use all my skill does it draw near. Yet its desire is slight and caution dominant. It approaches then retreats, trembling as if sensing machinery overhead. When I seize the moment, it flashes away like lightning, seeing my shadow and gone. Its quickness seems divine. After this, neither pipe nor bait can lure it. It sits indifferent, as if without male or female desire. How could I exploit any opening to display my art? This pheasant is most intelligent, most skilled at avoiding harm.

    "These three teach much about the world."

    Those who make reckless friendships, pursue sensuality without restraint, ignore warnings, defy stern fathers and good friends' reproofs—shameless, without caution, caught in their own snares, forever unaware—these are the first kind, easily trapped.

    Those who begin through desire and confusion but know danger looms and dare not indulge fully, who feel pangs of shame when caught and wish to reform—yet their old nature lingers. When loose companions seduce them and beautiful words call them, they forget their shame, retrace their old steps, and fall into ruin again—these are the second kind, trapped on the second throw.

    But those with noble character, who treasure purity and distance themselves from sensuality, who scorn debauchery and remain unmoved by loose companions' influence—when scheming friends pursue them with every art to make them like themselves, should one careless moment arise and they nearly fall into chaos, they recover, knowing shame. They cut such friends away, seek worthy companions, recall their errors with regret, resolve to improve daily with vigilance. They become fine people, their names honored for an age. These are the third kind—never trapped, free their whole lives.

    I reflected: my skill in crafting traps and hunting pheasants is exactly how loose companions lure the good into depravity.

    Ah, few pheasants escape the pipe and bait. Few people escape honeyed words. How sad! Does parental love wish for the first kind of capture? Or for a life of freedom? You must discern this distinction. Do not be careless.

    # The Tale of the Privy Bucket

    In the great market's secluded corner, the magistrate provided a privy bucket for urgent needs. Scholars who used it secretly faced accusations of indecency. In the neighborhood lived a man of standing whose worthless son secretly used it. His father discovered this and forbade it severely, yet the son would not listen. Day after day he used it without ceasing. The attendant wanted to stop him but feared the father's authority. All in the market condemned him, yet the son seemed pleased, as if he'd found an advantage. When careful men dared not use it, the son mocked them: "Coward! Why such fear? I use it daily without harm. What is there to fear?"

    Hearing of his son's shamelessness, the father summoned him and rebuked him: "The market is a sea of thousands. All eyes converge there. You, a scholar's son, openly in broad daylight, in full view, use that bucket. Do you feel no shame? You gain only the contempt and enmity of all—and perhaps misfortune follows. What possible benefit drives such boldness?"

    The son replied: "At first, when I saw any scholar using it, I spat at him and cursed him. One day my need was desperate. I tried the bucket and found great relief. After that, I could not feel ease without it. At first, when I used it, everyone mocked me. Yet over time, fewer did. Now many watch, yet none condemn me. If all watch without objection, surely my using it harms nothing."

    The father said: "Alas, you have already been abandoned. When all mocked you initially, it was because they still saw you as a scholar and hoped shame would reform you. When mockery decreased, they still regarded you as a scholar. Now when they watch without condemning, they do not regard you as human. Look at dogs and pigs relieving themselves in the street—do men mock them? When humans do wrong yet men do not mock, it is only because such humans are no longer considered human. Is this not the deepest sorrow?"

    The son said: "Outsiders do not condemn while you alone do. The distant judge impartially; the close judge with feeling. Why do the impartial not condemn while the feeling do?"

    The father answered: "It is precisely because they judge impartially that, seeing your wrong, they abandoned you—regard you as a thing—and pass judgment no more. That justice is merciless. It is precisely because I judge with feeling that, seeing your wrong, my heart aches and I desperately hope for your reform. That feeling is sorrowful. Yet observe: in a world without parents, none would guide anyone. After I am gone, you will understand my words."

    The son left and told others: "My old father lacks understanding. He forbids me without reason."

    Soon his father died. Afterward, the son went again to use the bucket. Suddenly wind rose behind his head. A poison club struck his brow. He collapsed senseless. Reviving, he seized the attacker: "What dead thing dares strike me? I have used this place nearly ten years. Not one person in the market has objected. What dead thing dares this?"

    The attacker replied: "The whole market has endured long. Now we repay. You still speak?"

    They bound him, placed him in the market center, and pelted him with broken pottery and stones. His household carried him home. He did not rise for a month. At last he recalled his father's teachings. Weeping bitterly, he reproached himself: "Father's words were true! A blade hides in laughter, true care hides in anger. Now, though I long to hear his wisdom, how can I attain it?"

    Sobbing uncontrollably, he kowtowed before his father's coffin and swore to reform. He became a good man.
